@node ideas  "Some Ideas on using the MusicWeb"

      Direct links to @{" Subsections " LINK ideas_subs}


    Unlike the more common variety of `Sequencer' program, which
    provides a fixed but limited set of immediately available uses,
    the MusicWeb is extremenly flexible, but requires that you build
    your own configuration from a set of basic functions to do what
    you want.  This is perhaps a new way of working, so you might like
    some orientation.  Also, the functions and usefulness of the various
    elements may not be immediately apparent, so I will try to give some
    general guidelines here.

    Bear in mind, though, that the MusicWeb is meant to be a partner
    to creativity, so the only way to take full advantage of it is
    to experiment!  Its flexibility makes this easy: you can rearrange
    and rebuild your configuration as you try it out, until you get
    the sound that's right.  We won't deal with the mechanics of building
    a diagram here, or the details of modules; refer to the nain manuals
    for these.  In this section we'll skim through some ideas and topics
    that don't fit well under other headings but may help you to tie
    the concepts together.

    The trick to using the MusicWeb successfully is to understand how
    the individual elements can work together to achieve a desired
    result.  At the simplest level of course, to get MIDI from your
    keyboard into the system, and send a -- probably transformed --
    stream out to your other equipment, your diagram will need a
    `MIDI In' element connected -- eventually -- to `MIDI Out'.
    However, a lot may go on in the paths between these two.
    Building up from a simple starting point -- branching off new
    paths and adding in more elements -- you can end up with something
    quite complex, but this needn't worry you, as you've created it
    in a series of small, simple steps.

    In fact for many purposes MIDI In or Out, or both, might even
    be absent.  If you're playing a prerecorded piece, you might leave
    out ~MIDI In', or if you're using internal voices only there might
    be no `MIDI Out', all paths feeding `Instrument' elements.
    (Incidentally, remember that MIDI In and Out are special in that
    there can only be one of each in a diagram, but you can have as
    many Instruments -- or any other element -- as you like.)

    Some elements are simple enough to do what they're required to
    on their own.  `Loudness' -- which alters the Velocity value
    of the Note-on events passing through it --, and `Transpose'
    -- for shifting notes up and down the scale --, are good examples.
    Simply insert one of these between MIDI In and MIDI Out and you
    can directly control that aspect of the event stream.  Don't
    forget, too, that all elements have an output connector, so
    that you don't have to terminate a path at, say, an Instrument:
    it can be carried on through to provide further outputs, be
    recorded, and so on.  In fact it is usually slightly more efficient
    to put a string of elements on a single path than to make excessive
    branches.

    By `chaining' elements in a a path, you can apply successive
    transformations and operations to the MIDI stream.  You could
    perhaps build the path:  Midi In -> Instrument -> Transpose
    -> MIDI Out, load some sample into the Instrument, and set the
    Transpose to shift notes down an octave.  This would give you
    a combination of an internal voice and your synth's output
    (shifted).  Naturally you could equally well do: MIDI In ->
    MIDI Out -> Transpose -> Instrument, for a different effect.


    Instead of operating simply sequentially on the stream, you
    can split the stream into several parallel ones with `branch points'.
    As a start, you could branch the path from MIDI In, feed one fork
    direct to MIDI Out, but insert a `Set Channel' in the other before
    feeding it to MIDI Out also.  Then you would be driving two channels
    of your synth at once with the same note.  (Or use a Transpose too,
    and have them an octave apart).  And so on.


    More significantly, a lot of specific functions are
    achieved by particular combinations of elements.  Let's
    look at the possibilities of Keyboard Range splitting as
    an initial example.  (This is @{" Keyboard Split " LINK Examples.GUIDE/split} in the Examples.)

    [I should point out before we get into this that there may be
    some unfortunate confusion in the use of the term "Filter".
    Elements in the Web that act on a data stream were originally called
    Filters by analogy with fairly standard computer usage (a la unix).
    Some elements in the MusicWeb are more specifically Filters, in
    that they can "comb out" certain events -- and have "Filter" in
    their label --, but even a simple Loudness element is a Filter
    in the Web sense.]

  Filtering and Splitting

    One of the supplied modules is `Key Range', which has sliders for
    setting upper and lower limits on a range of notes.  It also has
    a cycle gadget labelled `Function:'.  By initial default, this
    is set to `Block', and in this mode the element acts "stand alone"
    simply to filter out all note events outside the set range.  So one
    straightforward way to build a keyboard split would be to branch the
    original path (with the forks eventually proceeding on to whatever
    you wanted to do with the results of the split) and insert a Key
    Range element in each branch, with its limits suitably set.

    This might sometimes be an appropriate way to do it -- if we
    wanted overlap for instance -- but we more probably want a true
    split, where notes within the range go in one direction and those
    outside it in the other; we don't want to change sliders in two
    elements to adjust a single split range.  A better solution here
    is to use both a (single) Key Range and a `MIDI Splitter' element
    following it. Instead of using the default `Block' mode, we set
    the Key Range cycle gadget to one of the `Mark...' settings (in
    this simple case it doesn't matter which, as the MIDI Splitter
    responds to all of them by default). Now, none of the events are
    blocked out: instead, those outside the range are "marked", and
    when they encounter the splitter are diverted down the alternate
    path, while unmarked ones continue on the direct route.

    But... now that we have the note events going where we want, what
    about other events like the Sustain pedal (and anything else we
    might want on both paths)?  They continue along the direct path, and
    will never appear on the `diverted' one!  Well, a little elaboration
    easily fixes this.  We precede the above elements with a `Msg Filter'
    (which selects different classes of MIDI event messages in the same
    sort of way as Key Filter) and another MIDI Split, and set them to
    divert all the event types we want to have on both sides of the split;
    then we merge them in at some convenient later point of each branch.
    (Remember that any filter will accept up to three merging inputs, so
    there will probably be several "convenient points".  If not, use
    a `Join' element)

    There are other `Filters' (in the restricted sense) that
    respond to particular event properties in the same way. `Key Filter'
    selects certain notes within the octave, and `Chan Filter' selects
    a subset of MIDI channels.  `Vel Filter' marks note-on events with
    greater than the set Velocity value; however it has no (fairly useless)
    `Block' mode.  `Block Sys Msg' on the other hand doesn't do anything
    but block MIDI System Messages (like "Clock" and "Active Sense") that
    are often unneeded and can be an annoyance if you want to trigger a
    recording for example.

    For more complex setups, the availability of four separate Marks
    may be useful, as each splitter may be set to respond to one or
    any combination of them.  A splitter clears all the marks it is
    set to respond to, but doesn't touch others, so a series of filters
    can set a combination of marks on an event, which then have different
    effects as it proceeds through its own sequence of splitters.


    Right.  Now we have a path split into a couple of branches.
    What do we do with it?  That is determined largely by your
    imagination.  If you just want to drive different voices on
    a Synth connected to MIDI Out, you can insert a `Set Channel'
    element in each branch, set to the appropriate channel for each
    voice, and merge them back onto the MIDI Out element.  Or you
    might want one (or both) of the branches to drive two voices
    of the Synth for a `fatter' sound: place yet another Set Channel
    and connect it in a parallel path with the first.

    Elaborate this as you like.  Maybe insert a `Transpose' to shift
    one of the voices up or down an octave, or add in a short `Delay'.
    Instead of -- or in addition to --  external channels, you could
    direct some of the streams through `Instrument' elements to play
    8SVX samples.  You can try out and modify each idea as you go.
    As I said, experimentation is a `must' with the MusicWeb...

  MIDI Channels

    Internally, the MusicWeb doesn't pay much attention to the
    Channel values of MIDI events, except for the two relevant modules,
    `Set Channel' and `Chan Filter'.  Events retain the channel they
    had on entry to the system, unless you specifically set them to
    another with Set Channel.

    Elements other than these two respond to all events that they are
    concerned with, ignoring their channel.  `Instrument', for example,
    plays all note-events that arrive -- you would make it respond to a
    single channel by having an appropriate Chan Filter somewhere in its
    incoming path.

    Specific channels are mostly relevant when driving an external
    instrument, unless for some reason you have more than one channel
    coming in.  It is very likely that input to `MIDI In' will only be on
    one channel, unless you have some external merging hardware, or have
    used your keyboard's own split facilities, so you will be using
    other properties of the events to select and manipulate (until you
    want to send them back out).  If you do have separate channels
    coming in, and you want to keep them apart, use Chan Filter and
    MIDI Splitter combinations to do so.

    One place though that you will be concerned with channels is when
    playing a prerecorded file (or recording one).  The only way to keep
    streams and voices separate there is by giving them separate channels.
    Your configuration will need to include suitable channel setting and
    filtering to handle this.


  Types of Packets

    In using the MusicWeb, it's useful to know something about the
    way data is passed around the configuration.  One of the unique
    features of the Web scheme is the way different types of data can
    share the configuration -- even the same paths -- without conflicting.
    Most of the packets which pass from element to element contain MIDI
    events, but distinct from these are the `Sequence' packets that
    some of the modules deal with.  (To be truthful, these contain
    MIDI too, but in much larger chunks, and additionally have timing
    and other information needed to play the contents as a sequence.)
    Then (if you have the licensed version) you also have `Control
    Messages'; these currently are just used for switching paths within
    the configuration, but have the potential for controlling almost
    any aspect of the setup.

    Although all the modules in the MusicWeb's set process or respond
    to MIDI packets, only those concerned with recording will pay any
    attention to Sequence packets.  If you feed a Sequence packet to
    an element like Transpose, for example, it just goes straight
    through, so there's no harm in sharing a path like that.  However,
    you do have to take care that by merging paths or something a Sequence
    doesn't eventually end up where you don't want it to.

    For instance, the single input connector on a `RePlay' element
    serves several distinct functions: you can feed it a MIDI stream
    to be recorded, but you can also send it a Sequence, directly from
    another element, that will immediately become its new contents; then
    again, if `Trigger' mode is set, *any* arriving packet will initiate
    the triggered action. This can be useful -- you can have `Play'
    triggered so that it starts automatically when a Sequence is supplied
    -- but it could be very annoying if a Sequence accidentally arrived
    and replaced what you had just recorded!  So share paths with care.

  Recording and Playback

    The record and playback faclities of the MusicWeb are very different
    from the average Sequencer; in some ways more flexible, in others
    more limited.  Taking the limitations first, the main one is that
    there is no variable tempo playback -- sequences always play back
    exactly as they were recorded.  You can't edit sequences, either:
    the Web is oriented more to direct manipulation, so at the moment
    you will still have to use another program to do editing.  Saving
    your sequence as a MIDIFile is one way to do this.

    On the other hand, as a `RePlay' element is just another element,
    you can plug instances into your diagram anywhere, and have as
    many of them as you like.  Playing a sequence in one element and
    re-recording it in another with modifications or (live) additions
    is trivial.  To ensure that the recordings at each stage remain
    in step, you should make good use of the `triggered' Record mode:
    use it when you record the original sequence, so that it begins
    exactly on the first note you play, then again when you make the
    copy, so ithat it is triggered by that same recorded event.

    Sequencer programs usually have a number of parallel "tracks"
    into which you can successively record parts of your piece
    simultanously with the playback of previously recorded tracks.
    The MusicWeb lacks such a built-in concept of course, but you
    can get much the same effect by a configuration with several
    RePlay elements working in parallel.  As long as you trigger
    them all with the same event, they will play (or record) in
    exact synchrony.  How you trigger is up to you, and to the
    requirements of the moment; the first note from your keyboard
    might be a convenient choice, or perhaps some other event you
    can generate, such a a Program Change -- it doesn't have to be
    a meaningful event.

    One scheme for doing this that I find particularly useful is
    to have an extra RePlay (i.e. one that isn't used for track
    recording) set up as a "Lead-In".  You can use the `null' Control
    Message this generates at the end of a sequence (see RePlay docs)
    to trigger all the tracks at once.  What you do is to record a
    short phrase -- or a metronome 4-beat perhaps -- that will give
    you a lead in but not be recorded itself.  Then you loop this
    continuously, adjusting the delay slider until the rhythm is
    steady.  When you've got this to your satisfaction, you can switch
    to a `once through' playback mode, set the triggers on the `track'
    RePlay elements you want to run, start the lead-in again, and the
    null message will be just at the right point to trigger all the
    tracks. (You will have to separate out the control message from
    the MIDI events so they don't themselves trigger anything -- or get
    recorded.  A Msg Filter set to mark *all* events, and a MIDI Splitter,
    achieve this easily.)  [This example also shows the problem of trying
    to describe Web diagrams verbally!  If you're confused, look at the
    "2-Track" configuration included in the examples.  Refer to the
    description of that for more details too.]

    Instead of putting RePlay elements in parallel, you can chain them
    sequentially, using the same null-control-message technique.  This
    way you could record successive sections of a piece in turn, and have
    each trigger the next.  There are some subtleties to think about
    though.  For one thing, the null message can be no earlier than
    the last event in the sequence, so there's no way you can overlap
    successive sequences this way.  If you want to start a sequence
    before its predecessor has ended, you would have to have some
    trigger recorded in the sequence (but remember Control Messages
    are never recorded); again you could use the good old Program
    Change or some such.

  Sequences and MIDIFiles

    A RePlay element itself can save a sequence to a file, or reload
    it, but this file is in its own non-standard image format, so you
    can't use it with any other program.  However it can send sequences
    to other elements, and also receive them.  In particular, it can
    communicate with the `Write MIDI File' and `Read MIDI File' modules
    which handle the standard machine-independent MIDIfile format.

    To be able to write MIDIfiles, simply connect the `Sequence' output
    of the RePlay to a `Write MIDI File'.  Every time you click the
    `Send' button in the RePlay's control panel, the current sequence
    gets sent (as a single packet) to the other element, which pops
    up a requester in which you can specify filename and directory.

    Similarly, to read files, connect a ~Read MIDI File' output
    connector to the input of your RePlay (using a `Join' if you
    have other inputs as well).  A control panel button on the former
    pops up the file selection requester, and the file that you read
    in gets turned into a sequence and sent to the RePlay.

    Of course you can also couple the Sequence output connector of one
    RePlay to the input of another, to directly transfer a sequence.
    You might want. for example, to move a sequence from the element
    you recorded it on to another for playing back, so you could then
    re-record while adding another layer.

@endnode

@node priority  "Module Process Priorities"

    While the MusicWeb is running, there are quite a number of independent
    processes alive in the machine.  As you probably know, such processes
    can be set to different system `priorities' to determine which is
    seen as the most important when the system has to arbitrate time
    between them.

    Most of the processes do not need any special consideration, and
    can be left at the default (`0') priority, but there a few that
    are best set higher to improve performance markedly.  To be specific,
    they should have higher priority than Intuition (20), or you will get
    stuttering in the MIDI stream every time you move, open, or close
    a window.  The supplied `Run_WEB' script used by the startup icons
    does this for you, but you may want to know the rationale.

    The most important high-priority processes are the `Travellers'.
    These do most of the work along the paths of the diagram, so they
    had better not be slowed down.  They are invoked automatically by
    the Web as needed, so the control program must be told in the command
    line what value to use. This is achieved by the `TPRI' command line
    option you will see in the script.

    Most of the operations performed on the MIDI events are actually
    done by procedures called by the Travellers themselves, so the
    modules that are supplying those procedures don't need their own
    high priority.  One or two, though, are data sources, or accept the
    data into their own process, and so also should have their priority
    boosted.  One of these of course is the `MIDILink' module that
    provides `MIDI In' and `MIDI Out' and makes the actual connection
    to the serial port.  `MIDI_Instr' is also normally run at high
    priority.

    `RePlay' may also be given a high priority to keep the sequence
    smooth while windows are being moved and so on, but there is an
    as-yet-unlocated glitch that will lock your system if you happen
    to delete a high-priority RePlay while it is playing.  As long as
    you stop Play first this isn't a problem, but to be on the safe
    side it has been given an intermediate priority -- lower than
    Intuition, but higher than normal programs -- in the distribution.

    There is one other module -- `Delay' -- that really should also have
    high priority, but Run_WEB does not set it.  Why?  Because you could
    accidentally draw a diagram with a path looping back from the `Delayed'
    output to the input, and if you have zero delay set on the slider,
    feeding a packet to that configuration would immediately lock up
    your system!  (The data would go round and round without ever giving
    another task -- including Intuition, which manages the control panel
    -- a chance.)  If you think you can avoid doing this, you may prefer
    to edit Run_WEB to set its priority to 31 like the others.

    (If you're ahead of me, you may have noticed that you can create
    all sorts of other loops in the diagram if you want to, so you'll
    wonder why those won't lock things up too.  Well, there is protection
    built in that prevents the same `Traveller trip' going on forever,
    but this is reset each time the trip starts, so that it doesn't
    protect the Delay module -- as the Traveller starts from there --
    from an endless loop.)

@endnode

